#Text=John Dennys
#Text=Title page of first edition ( 1613)in the Bodleian , shelfmark 8vo .
#Text=D 15 Art .
#Text=Court House at Pucklechurch , Gloucester
#Text=John Dennys ( died 1609 ) , a poet and fisherman , pioneered Angling poetry in England .
#Text=His only work The Secrets of Angling was the earliest English poetical treatise on fishing .
#Text=John Dennys may have been an acquaintance of Shakespeare .
#Text=Early life
#Text=John Dennys was son of Hugh Dennis ( died 1559 ) [ 1 ] [ 2 ] [ nb 1 ] of " Plucherchurch " and Katherine , daughter of Thomas Trye of Hardwicke , Gloucestershire . [ 3 ] [ 4 ] [ nb 2 ]

#Text=Sir Harris Nicholas reported that he was the younger son of Sir Walter Dennys of Pucklechurch and Agnes Danvers or Davers , and The Secrets of Angling was written a century earlier than believed .
#Text=Ellacombe claims that Sir Walter and Katherine were his great-grand parents .
#Text=The author of the article claimed that Ellacombe had the correct genealogy of author John Dennis . [ 3 ]
#Text=The introductions of the 1883 and 1885 The Secrets of Angling editions state that it is believed that John 's father was Hugh and his mother was Katherine Trye . [ 5 ] [ 6 ]
#Text=Watkins , his biographer , said that Ellacombe 's account was " correcting Sir Harris Nicolas 's account " . [ 1 ] [ nb 3 ] [ 2 ] [ nb 1 ]
#Text=Hugh 's father John had been the heir of Hugh Denys of Osterley , Middlesex ( died 1511 ) , Groom of the Stool to Henry VII . [ 7 ] [ 8 ] [ nb 4 ]
#Text=John 's elder brother Henry , died without having fathered any children . [ 2 ] [ 4 ] [ nb 1 ]
#Text=The Secrets of Angling
#Text=The River Boyd at Doynton
#Text=His only work The Secrets of Angling was the earliest English poetical treatise on fishing . [ 10 ] [ nb 5 ]
#Text=In it he wrote of a brook , River Boyd , formed from streams in his hometown of Pucklechurch , which met downstream with the River Avon : [ 1 ]
#Text=And thou , sweet Boyd , that with thy watry sway , Dost wash the cliffs of Deignton and of Weeke ; And through their Rockes with crooked winding way , Thy mother
#Text=Avon runnest soft to seeke ; In whose fayre streames the speckled Trout doth play . [ 1 ]
#Text=It was first published in 1613 . [ 11 ] [ 12 ]
#Text=Dennys 's book was published after his death , the author identified by the initials J.D. , and had been attributed to up to 6 poets .
#Text=In 1811 the authorship was determined from Stationers ' Registers , which showed that Dennys authored the book . [ 1 ]

#Text=A didactic pastoral poem in 3 books , totalling 151 verses each of 8 lines , in the style of Virgil 's Georgics , it was published in 4 editions until 1652 , examples of which are amongst the rarest books in existence . [ 12 ]
#Text=Verses from the book have been quoted in other works , [ 13 ] such as Izaak Walton in the first part of the first chapter of his 1653 edition of The Compleat Angler . [ 14 ] [ nb 6 ]
#Text=Dennys received at the hand of Thomas Westwood ( 1814 – 1888 ) , the epithet " The Fisherman 's Glorious John " . [ 15 ]
#Text=The appellation was received from Walter Scott . [ 16 ]
#Text=Marriage and children
#Text=He married Eleanor , daughter of Thomas Millett of Warwickshire [ 3 ] [ 4 ] [ nb 7 ] and had the following children : [ 2 ] [ nb 1 ]
#Text=Henry [ 4 ] ( born 1594 ) , [ 17 ]
#Text=High Sheriff of Gloucestershire ( 1629 ) , died on 26 June 1638 and may also have been buried the same day at Pucklechurch . [ 18 ] [ nb 8 ]
#Text=William , born 1596 and baptised 18 April 1596 [ 4 ] buried at Pucklechurch 1652 .
#Text=Cicely or Cecelia , born 1596 and baptised 18 April 1596 , married William Guise , Esquire of Elmore and Sheriff of Gloucester in 1647 . [ 4 ] [ 19 ]
#Text=Katherine , born 1599 and baptised 9 April 1599 [ 4 ]
#Text=Between 1572 and 1608 , he was the lord of the manor at Oldbury-sur-Montem , Pucklechurch , Glocestershire . [ 1 ] [ 3 ] [ 20 ]
#Text=He had other places in the same county . [ 3 ]
#Text=Acquaintanceship with Shakespeare
#Text=Rev. Henry Nicholson Ellacombe wrote Shakespeare as an Angler , in which he argues that The Bard and John Dennys ( Dennis ) may have known each other .
#Text=William Shakespeare lived for a while at Dursley , not too far from Dennys 's manor of Oldbury-on-Hill , north of Pucklechurch . [ 20 ] [ 21 ]
#Text=Death and epitaph
#Text=He died 30 July 1609 and was buried 7 August 1609 at the ancient Pucklechurch , [ 3 ] [ 18 ] [ nb 9 ]
#Text=The family was buried in the Pucklechurch 's " ancient " church on the north aisle . [ 1 ] [ 3 ]
#Text=John Dennys 's will was dated 1609 , without month , proved 14th . Oct. 1609 . [ 22 ]
#Text=Thomas Westwood wrote the following epitaph for John Dennys :
#Text=Calm be his sleep in the old aisle of Pucklechurch !

#Text=or if any sound reach him from the outer world , may it be only the soughing of the sweet south wind , and the ripple of Boyd , that with " crooked winding way " past cliff and meadow , " Its mother Avon runneth soft to seek " . [ 23 ]
